The paper deals with efficient computation of SimRank, a similarity measure between nodes in a graph, which is a problem in graph algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The focus is on processing single source SimRank queries in real-time, which is relevant to information retrieval (cs.IR) and search engines. The paper also discusses the scalability of the proposed algorithm to massive graphs with frequent updates, which is relevant to database systems (cs.DB) and computational engineering (cs.CE). Finally, the paper proposes a novel algorithmic design that identifies a small number of relevant nodes, which is relevant to social networks and influence maximization (cs.SI).
